=====================================================================

The Wired Reflexes hum at the base of your skull as you push through
the Cinder Block's door. Your nervous system is running hot — three
cups of soykaf and no sleep will do that. The pheromones are working
overtime; you can feel it in the way the ganger by the door steps
aside without being asked.

Cinders looks up as you walk in. Her chrome eye tracks you for a
moment longer than her meat one. She recognizes you. Taps the bar
twice with her knuckles.

"Stopgap. You're late. Someone's been asking for you."

She nods toward a booth in the back. A man in a tailored suit sits
there, sipping synth-tea. He's clean, too clean for the Barrens. No
visible chrome, but that means nothing — the expensive stuff hides.
His eyes meet yours. He smiles, but it doesn't reach his eyes.

Your Wired Reflexes flag three exits. The pheromones won't work
through the booth's air filter — you can see the faint shimmer of it.

"Sit. We have business."

What do you do?

